  "why": "TESTRNN applies semantic-preserving mutations at each step (e.g., EDA mutations for text, RDKit-preserving SMILES enumeration, small Gaussian noise for images/videos) and explicitly aims to preserve the naturalness of perturbations. However, the paper does not describe an explicit mechanism that enforces or bounds cumulative distortion across repeated mutation iterations relative to the original seed (e.g., limiting total perturbation magnitude from the seed or restricting search to a learned realistic distribution). The algorithm records each test case's original seed (orig) and uses an oracle radius when classifying adversarial inputs, but mutated inputs are still added to the pool and re-mutated without an explicit cumulative-distortion control. These facts match the metric definition for 'Medium': per-step plausibility-preserving mutations are used, but cumulative distortion across iterations is not explicitly controlled.",
  "evidence": "p.1191 Abstract: \"...owing to its working with finer temporal semantics and the consideration of the naturalness of input perturbation.\"; p.1198 Sec. VI-B(1) Random Mutation: \"When the LSTM input has continuous values (e.g., image input), Gaussian noises with fixed mean and variance are added to the input. Meanwhile, for discrete value input (e.g., IMDB movie reviews for sentiment analysis), a set of problem-specific mutation functions M are defined.\"; p.1199 Sec. VII-A(3) Input Mutation: \"To avoid this, we take a set M of mutants from the EDA toolkit [48], ... This ensures the mutated text paragraphs are always valid.\" and \"For Lipophilicity model, we take a set M of mutants that change the SMILES string without affecting the molecular structure it represents... The enumerated SMILES strings are the test cases.\"; p.1196 Sec. VI (Algorithm 1 / main loop): \"x' <- m(x); T <- T ∪ {x'}; orig[x'] <- orig[x]\" and \"Newly generated test inputs are added into T (Line 7), where they are queued for the next iteration.\" (shows mutated inputs are re-used for further mutation); p.1198 Sec. VI-C(1) Test Oracle: \"We define a set of norm-balls, each of which is centered around a data sample with known label. The radius r_oracle of norm-balls intuitively means that a human cannot differentiate between inputs within a norm ball... A test case x' is said to not pass the oracle if x' is within the norm-ball of some known sample x, i.e., ||x - x'||2 ≤ r_oracle, and if x' has a different classification from x.\" (shows oracle compares to original seed) ."
